    &gt; 
    &gt; 
    &gt; In the collection framework when creating a sorted set a 
    &gt; Comparator is
    &gt; passed in as an argument.  If the Comparator argument is null the
    &gt; compareTo() on the elements is called.
    &gt; 
    &gt; I am not sure what use an assertGreaterThan( Collection, 
    &gt; Collection)
    &gt; makes much sense.   In mathematics it&#39;s not possible to 
    &gt; say one vector
    &gt; is greater than another, unless they are projected onto a 
    &gt; given axis.
    &gt; This is not really possible on your average collection of objects.
    &gt; 
    &gt; I think the only two useful cases are...
    &gt; 
    &gt; assertEquals(Collection, Collection);
    &gt; assertEquals(Collection, Collection, Comparator );
    &gt; 
    &gt; Passing in a null Comparator to the second method would 
    &gt; behave like when
    &gt; passing a Comparator to a sorted set, equals() method (or 
    &gt; compareTo())
    &gt; would be called on the elements.  
    &gt; 
    &gt; 
    &gt; Dave
